AcceptedAnswer:
I prove this inequality does not use induction, but I think this proof also elementary proof, because this proof does not use calculus. $$\begin{array}{lcl}
\left( 1+\frac{1}{n}\right)^n &=& 1+\binom{n}{1} \frac{1}{n}+ \sum_{k=2}^n\binom{n}{k} \frac{1}{n^k}\\ &=&2+\sum_{k=2}^n \frac{1}{k!} \frac{n(n-1)\cdots (n-k+1)}{n^k}\\
&\le& 2+\sum_{k=2}^n \frac{1}{k!} \le  2+\sum_{k=2}^n \frac{1}{k(k-1)} \\ &=& 3-\frac{1}{n}
\end{array}
$$

